Dominica has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Dominica, see Return to the UK
Local measures
A State of Emergency is in place but restrictions are being gradually eased. Emergency regulations have been extended from 11 May to 28 May. A pass system is in operation, obtainable from the Dominica Police.
From 7pm to 5am Monday to Friday and from Saturday 6pm to Monday 5am a total lockdown continues in place unless offering or accessing an essential service. On Mondays to Saturdays people can access or provide retail services including supermarkets, medical, gas stations, clothing and textile, appliances and electronics stores. Law and accountancy firms are permitted to offer their services.
It is mandatory to wear masks outside the home. Beaches and rivers may be accessed 8am to 5pm Monday to Saturday but no alcohol consumption, picnics, music or gatherings of more than 10 people are permitted. Schools, gyms, beauty salons, bars and churches remain closed.
For more information, go to the Dominica Government Information Service on Facebook
See Return to the UK
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
